window.docContents[37].resolve({"/Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic/Exercises/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic--Exercises":{"contents":"Prove each statement in Lean, replacing sorry with a proof. Download the exercise file Lecture01.lean and open it in VS Code.\n\n\n\nExercise 1. Implication composes.\n\ntheorem exercise1 (P Q R : Prop)\n    (hPQ : P → Q) (hQR : Q → R) : P → R := by\n  sorry\n\n\nExercise 2. Conjunction distributes over disjunction.\n\ntheorem exercise2 (P Q R : Prop) :\n    P ∧ (Q ∨ R) ↔ (P ∧ Q) ∨ (P ∧ R) := by\n  sorry\n\n\nExercise 3. Disjunction associates.\n\ntheorem exercise3 (P Q R : Prop) :\n    (P ∨ Q) ∨ R → P ∨ (Q ∨ R) := by\n  sorry\n\n\nExercise 4. This direction of the first De Morgan law is constructive.\n\ntheorem exercise4 (P Q : Prop) : ¬P ∨ ¬Q → ¬(P ∧ Q) := by\n  sorry\n\n\nExercise 5. Peirce's law.C. S. Peirce, On the Algebra of Logic: A Contribution to the Philosophy of Notation, American Journal of Mathematics 7(2), 1885, pp. 180–196. It requires classical reasoning; consider a case analysis on Classical.em P.\n\ntheorem exercise5 (P Q : Prop) : ((P → Q) → P) → P := by\n  sorry\n\n\n","context":"Formal Software Verification\u0009Lecture 1: Motivation and Propositional Logic","header":"1.6. Exercises","id":"/Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic/Exercises/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic--Exercises"}});